Those mini get-a-ways mean so much. Just a day or two break needs to happen when you are running all crazy "on the grind." Our family friend "Jig" 🤣 turned 50 and celebrated with an invite to experience a ski trip to Winter Park, Colorado. Tight that she didn't book a Caribbean island🤣, I went with the thought of just chillin' with hot cocoa by a fireplace. But she had all types of adventures for us.

The main one I was excited about was finally getting a chance to go snowmobiling! My wife didn't ride with me cus I crashed us into a 10 ft deep river bank on an ATV in Costa Rica (not a scratch on us🙏🏾) in 2021. So I don't blame her🤣. But my inner Evil Knievel can never settle, so I rev'd up that Ski-Doo and hit this crazy mountain. They told us to stay clear of Devil's Thumb if we could, but of course I ended up in this dangerous part of the mountain (by mistake! Those signs are mad small!😫) til my ears started poppin', only one trail of ski track ahead of me and a few animal footprints showed up in the snow.😮🦌I went waaay too far.

The serenity of driving up a rough ass mountain by my self at speeds I shouldn't have  was adrenaline inducing and mind clearing. No voices, no music, no hassles...just me, snowy nature and my thoughts. It felt damn near meditative. Lots of answers for long time questions came into view. Clarity. Calm. Creativeness.

Round trip traveling to Colorado to stay as quick as the journey was a task, but it was well worth the good times and laughs had with all that attended. Time with others and self is a must. I won't neglect myself any more when that feeling hits.

Happy birthday and thanks for this trip Jig! I'm snowmobile ready everytime now! (I should have jumped to Sundance next door haha!).

I hurriedly grabbed my phone to catch this beautiful moment between legendary brothers @quincyjones and #ClarenceAvant at the 2018 City of Hope dinner in LA.

Seeing them chat it up before the honoring of #JonPlatt was in its own way an honor. Two iconic  battle worn generals showing brotherly love. They probably spoke earlier that day...that's how close we know them to be.

A few weeks before this picture was taken, I attended Mr. Jones' documentary screening after-party. I was intent on meeting Mr. Jones and explain my position as the Editor-In-Chief of VIBE (what a convo). Before that meeting, I walked in the venue just as Mr. Avant and his lovely wife Jacqueline (🙏🏾) were walking out hand in hand. 

With just us three in the entry way, I introduced myself and saluted Mr. Avant and all he has done for us in the entertainment industry and black culture as a whole.

"Thank you young man," he said with the dim lights around us making our chat cinematic. "I know you are here to support your guy tonight..." I started. "But, your story needs to be told in similar fashion. People need your journey for inspiration too." Mrs. Avant smiled at him knowingly and Mr. Avant replied assuredly, "My story will be told soon. It's on the way. You'll see." We shook hands and I wished them safe travels home.

Seeing the loving couple together like that was such a joy. Seeing the documentary on his life, 'The Black Godfather' that came out a year later like he said, was glorious as well. That excellent work of research and respect, done impeccably by the great @reggiehudlin, informed us of monumental moves by Mr. Avant that he never even spoke of before.

His life wasn't just a black executive that made deals. Mr. Avant created life connections that helped set the foundation of the Russell's, Diddy's, Jay's, to the @badassboz, @larryjackson and so many more in politics, education and various industries.

Watch the doc. It explains what it takes to make it in entertainment as a black man where your talent isn't acting, singing, dancing, playing an instrument...where your talent is the passion for people bonding & building.

Rest well legend and thank you for your service 🙏🏾.

@google Cloud Next hosted the transformative leadership workshop [Examined] Human in San Francisco. Think of a deep dive into your learned bias, cultural behaviors, business practices all wrapped into your personality traits... dissected and broken down to help you become your best human to assist others in doing the same.

This leadership workshop was attended by the sharpest most successful people from the biggest companies in the world. Yet, we all found out quickly how much work we need to do to improve our status quo in dealing with our staff, superiors and our personal lives. There is always room for improvement. Especially when you are a leader.

So many valuable realizations from this experience. Two in particular: that slide with the color beads in them... those beads represented answers to biz and personal questions. My answers shocked me visually as the white ones mainly account for those I answer to in my business dealings and the Black ones rep the majority of my personal interactions. Second was a transparent activity where we shared personal issues that we see and don't always show, but we bring into business and personal. The physical weights we had to put in backpacks and carry around really hit me hard.

I value this experience greatly, it was 10 hours of self work. The way visual and performance art was weaved in was genius. Leadership isn't an "I rule people stance." It's an "I feel people" one. We who have that responsibility must take it as an honor to lead and help others more.

Thank you Google Cloud for the time, education and fellowship networking with my new team (Table 3 Squad! Thanks for choosing me as our leader!💯)
